journals.title: In the Darkroom
journals.entry: Picture this: red glow, chemical smells, and me hunched over trays of film. It‚Äôs my secret lair‚Äîthe darkroom. Memories develop like Polaroids: Xavier‚Äôs first steps, Maya‚Äôs smile on our wedding day. Why do I do it? Because in that dim light, I weave our love into tangible art. Our walls? Covered in emotions.

journals.title: Claws and Connection
journals.entry: Cosplaying as Wolverine at the convention felt like stepping into another skin. The adamantium claws were heavy, but they connected me to something deeper. When I returned home, still in costume, Xavier toddled over. His tiny fingers traced the faux claws, and I realized: family bonds are our true superpower. Maya snapped a photo, and I vowed to cherish it forever.

journals.title: Capturing Moments
journals.entry: Today, the sun painted the park in hues of gold. I watched my son, little Xavier, chase after butterflies, his laughter echoing through the air. As a photographer, I couldn‚Äôt resist‚ÄîI snapped candid shots of his joy, preserving these fleeting moments. Later, I showed the photos to my wife, Maya. Her eyes softened, and she whispered, ‚ÄúYou capture our world beautifully, Jerome.‚Äù

journals.title: Today, I Saw Something...
journals.entry: I walked out of my barber shop today, minding my own business. Out of nowhere, up comes this man in a Viking helmet straight-up Flavor-Flav-style... and asked me for ten dollars. After declining, he made a brief battle cry and started jogging down the sidewalk in a galloping motion. Well, that's Charleston for you!

photo-memories.comment: This was my Great Grandma Gertrude as a little girl moving to our state with her family. In 1914, there weren't very many houses occupying land here. Crazy how it's grown into such a big city. You guys have all thrived in happiness here. So thankful for their choice long ago. Butterfly effects are a true thing of beauty at times.

The only picture of the service facility my great and great-great grandparents worked at and eventually managed. The hard work they put in every day to get to build that business along with unconditional love is what paved the way for our family's success here for generations up to today. Never forget what it took to get us where we are. We all love you!
It didn't start with us, but it WILL continue. Never forget to try your hardest, LOVE what you do, and be kind. My favorite picture of my amazing family. I couldn't be more appreciative.

about-me.title: Love For Vintage Vinyl Grooves
about-me.entry: Picture this: crackling records, soulful melodies, and a worn-out armchair. Vinyl spins magic‚Äîeach scratch tells a story. Whether it‚Äôs Coltrane‚Äôs sax or Aretha‚Äôs powerhouse vocals, these grooves transport me. Why do I love it? Because music isn‚Äôt just sound; it‚Äôs a time machine. And when the needle hits the groove, I‚Äôm dancing through decades.

about-me.title: My Favorite Espresso Blend
about-me.entry: When the sun peeks over the city skyline, I crave that rich, aromatic jolt‚Äîthe perfect espresso. My favorite blend? Dark roast with hints of cocoa and a dash of cinnamon. Why? Because it kickstarts my day like a turbocharged engine, fueling my hustle as a multi-unit franchise owner. Plus, sipping it feels like a secret handshake with the universe.

about-me.title: My Favorite Photographer
about-me.entry: Gerald Cyrus, man, he‚Äôs like a hidden gem. His photos? They‚Äôre like soul whispers frozen in time. You see, he captures life‚Äîthe raw, unfiltered stuff. Couples laughing in La Place, kids chasing dreams. And that black and white? It‚Äôs like nostalgia wrapped in silver gelatin. Cyrus gets it‚Äîhow every click tells a story, how moments become memories.

about-me.title: LEGOS!
about-me.entry: As my family already knows, I absolutely adore LEGOs. I have been a humor-based brick artist and photographer for 11 years, and I've loved every minute of what I do.

about-me.title: My Favorite Movies
about-me.entry:
I adore three quirky '80s and '90s films:

- ‚ÄúBuckaroo Banzai‚Äù: Brain surgery meets epic guitar solos, and evil aliens? Just misunderstood dance enthusiasts.
- ‚ÄúAliens‚Äù: Ellen Ripley‚Äôs survival skills involve xenomorph juggling and sassy one-liners. Extraterrestrial diplomacy, anyone?
- ‚ÄúThe Terminator‚Äù: Forget the apocalypse; focus on the forbidden love and molten steel. Schwarzenegger impressions included.
Life‚Äôs too short for serious sci-fi‚Äîpass the popcorn and let‚Äôs watch ‚ÄúE.T.‚Äù!
